h2>What is bandwidth? How is it measured?</h2>
<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>You might have heard about units such as =E2=80=9CMbps=E2=80=9D (megabit=
s/sec.), =E2=80=9CMB/s=E2=80=9D (megabytes/sec.) and even =E2=80=9CGbps=E2=
=80=9D (gigabits/sec) through your Internet Service Provider =E2=80=94 thes=
e are used to measure how much data, or =E2=80=9C<strong>bandwidth</strong>=
=E2=80=9D flows between two different devices. These units are often used i=
nterchangeably, but some have very different meanings. For instance, if you=
r home connection was =E2=80=9C1 Gbps=E2=80=9D (one gigabit/s), and you wri=
te =E2=80=9C1 GB/s,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99d be misrepresenting your maximum =
<strong>data throughput</strong> by a factor of 8! (1 gigabyte/s =3D 8 giga=
bit/s) </p>
<p>Having said that, units that have the =E2=80=9C/[time unit]=E2=80=9D not=
ation after their data size represent an average of how much data is being =
transferred/read over the period of time. In the case of copying a local fi=
le, one might see =E2=80=9C100 MB/s.=E2=80=9D This means that, on average, =
you are copying the file back onto a drive at an average of one hundred meg=
abytes per second. This is not a measure of size =E2=80=94 rather, it measu=
res an average at any instantaneous point in time. </p>
<h3>Total Data Transferred (ex. "Bandwidth Used")</h3>
<p>When you request an image, for example, you receive image data. This ima=
ge data has a size =E2=80=94 this size is generally measured in byte-based =
units (megabytes, gigabytes, even terabytes).</p>
<p>Using Content Delivery Networks (CDNs) as an example, suppose an Edge Se=
rver receives your request and performs necessary processing. When the serv=
er begins to return data, it is considered =E2=80=9Cegress.=E2=80=9D </p>
<p>Egress is most often the metric used for measuring usage as content deli=
very networks don=E2=80=99t have a lot of ingress by end-users. The only in=
gress usually occurs when a CDN pulls data from an origin server. </p>
<p>In short, the measure of total data transferred is the amount of data mo=
ved during a given time (egress + ingress). Some providers choose to measur=
e only ingress for "bandwidth." Regardless, it is important to understand t=
hat data transfer, in general, measures the amount of information you've se=
nt/received over a longer period of time (for instance, terabytes transferr=
ed a month).</p>
<h3>Data Rate or Throughput</h3>
<p><img src=3D"https://cdn.bunny.pictures/images/what-is-bandwidth-and-how-=
does-it-correlate-to-data-rate-and-data-throughput.svg" alt=3D"what is band=
width and how does it correlate to data rate and data throughput" title=3D"=
What is bandwidth and how does it correlate to data rate and data throughpu=
t"></p>
<p>In the previous section, "bandwidth" refers to how much data has been tr=
ansferred over a longer  period of time. <strong>Data rate</strong>, or dat=
a throughput, is different. It refers to a more <em>instantaneous</em> tran=
sfer speed. In other words, if we had a highway, bandwidth in this context =
refers to the theoretical number of cars that could flow per unit of time.<=
/p>
<h3>Conversion Chart</h3>
<p>For reference, all units used in this article are in the chart below:=20
1 GB =3D 1000 MB =3D 1000000 KB (used to measure total data transfer, rathe=
r than an average of data being transferred at a given point) </p>
<p>Measuring <em>transfer speeds</em>:</p>
<p>1 Gbit/second =3D 1000 Mbit/s=20
1 Mbit/second =3D 1000 Kbit/s</p>
<p>Measuring <em>total data transferred</em>:</p>
<p>1 TB =3D 1000 GB
1 GB =3D 1000 MB
1 MB =3D 1000 KB</p>
<p>Conversion from bytes -&gt; bits =3D <code>(total_bytes) * 8</code>
Conversion from bits -&gt; bytes =3D <code>(total_bits) / 8</code></p>
